00:41:07,882 --> 00:41:09,511
- Now...
- You could actually talk to me.

1201
00:41:09,512 --> 00:41:11,351
When I said something,

1202
00:41:11,352 --> 00:41:14,052
he responded, and we talked. We had a conversation.

1203
00:41:14,522 --> 00:41:16,522
- There are people who don't?
- We could communicate.

1204
00:41:16,722 --> 00:41:18,761
There are many people I can't communicate with.

1205
00:41:18,762 --> 00:41:20,961
- Not at all?
- Right.

1206
00:41:20,962 --> 00:41:24,232
You're the best at acting the role of a difficult customer.

1207
00:41:24,732 --> 00:41:26,362
You would be good at being a YouTuber who does that.

1208
00:41:27,132 --> 00:41:28,272
He's serious.

1209
00:41:28,372 --> 00:41:29,531
Should I make a side character?

1210
00:41:29,532 --> 00:41:31,442
- You'd do well.
- Stop making side characters.

1211
00:41:31,542 --> 00:41:33,642
He's good, but it would be funny only if he did it once or twice.

1212
00:41:34,672 --> 00:41:36,842
Why are you ruining this?

1213
00:41:36,942 --> 00:41:38,011
(Ho Dong becomes the thinking type only when it's about Yeong Cheol.)

1214
00:41:38,012 --> 00:41:39,112
Okay.

1215
00:41:39,382 --> 00:41:43,252
Next, we'll talk about their common aspects.

1216
00:41:43,552 --> 00:41:44,852
Their common aspect...

1217
00:41:45,422 --> 00:41:47,521
is that they're rebels in the survival scene.

1218
00:41:47,522 --> 00:41:49,821
You were all on a survival show, right?

1219
00:41:49,822 --> 00:41:51,791
- I watched all of them.
- Me too.

1220
00:41:51,792 --> 00:41:53,091
- He really likes survival shows.
- Really?

1221
00:41:53,092 --> 00:41:55,391
I watched all of them. I really did.

1222
00:41:55,392 --> 00:41:57,301
- Thank you.
- I really love them.

1223
00:41:57,302 --> 00:41:59,361
- I really...
- Yes.

1224
00:41:59,362 --> 00:42:03,172
watched the survival show RISABAE was on.

1225
00:42:03,372 --> 00:42:05,171
- She was so cool.
- That's right.

1226
00:42:05,172 --> 00:42:06,872
- Seriously.
- I wasn't cool.

1227
00:42:06,942 --> 00:42:09,041
(She was on "The Influencer," a show that determined...)

1228
00:42:09,042 --> 00:42:11,182
(who had the utmost influence on social media.)

1229
00:42:11,382 --> 00:42:14,412
(RISABAE showed the power of a beauty expert.)

1230
00:42:14,752 --> 00:42:15,951
- She's a star.
- I...

1231
00:42:15,952 --> 00:42:18,652
I used to watch her videos from time to time.

1232
00:42:18,822 --> 00:42:20,621
But after seeing her on the show,

1233
00:42:20,622 --> 00:42:21,922
I thought she was really cool.

1234
00:42:22,022 --> 00:42:23,622
- She is so cool.
- Her personality.

1235
00:42:23,752 --> 00:42:25,261
- That's right.
- Normally,

1236
00:42:25,262 --> 00:42:26,991
as the survival show progresses,

1237
00:42:26,992 --> 00:42:31,101
your flaws start to get exposed at certain points.

1238
00:42:31,102 --> 00:42:35,002
But she was perfect from beginning to end.

1239
00:42:35,132 --> 00:42:37,171
I realized that a person could truly have...

1240
00:42:37,172 --> 00:42:38,301
a great character.

1241
00:42:38,302 --> 00:42:41,271
I just did what I normally did.

1242
00:42:41,272 --> 00:42:43,071
I wasn't particularly good,

1243
00:42:43,072 --> 00:42:45,841
but I think people noticed my sincerity.

1244
00:42:45,842 --> 00:42:48,752
Can I go to sleep while I have the video playing?

1245
00:42:49,382 --> 00:42:53,021
(She felt sorry and thankful for her fans...)

1246
00:42:53,022 --> 00:42:56,591
(who supported her until late at night.)

1247
00:42:56,592 --> 00:42:59,621
I think they realized that I really wanted to give them the information,

1248
00:42:59,622 --> 00:43:03,461
and that I was serious about creating such interesting content.

1249
00:43:03,462 --> 00:43:06,201
- I think they saw my sincerity.
- "Can I go to sleep..."

1250
00:43:06,202 --> 00:43:08,431
"Can I doze off for a while?"

1251
00:43:08,432 --> 00:43:11,901
(An artist who moves hearts who also shone on a survival show.)

1252
00:43:11,902 --> 00:43:13,442
I was on a show with her before.

1253
00:43:13,642 --> 00:43:18,782
I thought about why RISABAE receives so much love.

1254
00:43:19,012 --> 00:43:20,642
She always thinks about...

1255
00:43:20,952 --> 00:43:23,312
- making the other person happy.
- That's right.

1256
00:43:23,382 --> 00:43:25,182
How she can make the person shine brighter.

1257
00:43:25,352 --> 00:43:27,692
That's her priority. She puts the others first.

1258
00:43:28,192 --> 00:43:30,551
- The opportunity came to you.
- She's kind.

1259
00:43:30,552 --> 00:43:32,621
- Thank you so much.
- Did you go to the same school?

1260
00:43:32,622 --> 00:43:33,791
No.

1261
00:43:33,792 --> 00:43:35,061
- Why...
- We were in a show together.

1262
00:43:35,062 --> 00:43:37,132
Did you go to Masan Yongma High School?

1263
00:43:38,262 --> 00:43:41,402
Right. I studied there.

1264
00:43:41,832 --> 00:43:44,341
- She...
- I studied in Masan.

1265
00:43:44,342 --> 00:43:46,142
That was why you were close.

1266
00:43:46,442 --> 00:43:49,772
Chungju Man. You're a civil servant. Why were you on "Game of Blood?"

1267
00:43:50,842 --> 00:43:52,911
- Shouldn't you...
- A game with the complaints?

1268
00:43:52,912 --> 00:43:55,681
- I also want to go back in time...
- A game with the complaints.

1269
00:43:55,682 --> 00:43:57,381
and tell myself not to go there.

1270
00:43:57,382 --> 00:43:59,681
Since it's a survival game, I focused there.

1271
00:43:59,682 --> 00:44:02,492
People have different ways of surviving.

1272
00:44:02,722 --> 00:44:06,192
I tried my best to play the role that was given to me.

1273
00:44:06,292 --> 00:44:10,231
(Source: Wavve)

1274
00:44:10,232 --> 00:44:14,232
(His bold play triggered dopamine rushes!)

1275
00:44:19,072 --> 00:44:20,142
Darn it.

1276
00:44:22,412 --> 00:44:24,942
(It made Jang Dong Min, a legend of survival shows, angry.)

1277
00:44:26,042 --> 00:44:30,452
(Chungju Man showed us the crazy side of office workers.)

1278
00:44:30,682 --> 00:44:34,052
So for the true fans of the survival show,

1279
00:44:34,592 --> 00:44:36,521
- it could have been disappointing.
- It could have been frustrating.

1280
00:44:36,522 --> 00:44:38,991
For those who thought it was new, they might have liked it.

1281
00:44:38,992 --> 00:44:41,362
- I watched the entire show.
- Yes.

1282
00:44:41,462 --> 00:44:42,891
What I think is,

1283
00:44:42,892 --> 00:44:45,602
he got eliminated even though it wasn't his time.

1284
00:44:46,102 --> 00:44:47,602
But why did you do that, Orbit?

1285
00:44:47,972 --> 00:44:50,072
You can't defend Orbit?

1286
00:44:50,402 --> 00:44:54,372
There is a standard in which I decide the shows I go to.

1287
00:44:54,572 --> 00:44:56,571
I go to shows to talk about science.

1288
00:44:56,572 --> 00:44:58,612
Making science popular is my life goal.

1289
00:44:58,942 --> 00:45:00,542
I rejected the offer at first,

1290
00:45:00,812 --> 00:45:02,681
but I was told the show will be dubbed...

1291
00:45:02,682 --> 00:45:04,052
- and released in 190 countries.
- Right.

1292
00:45:04,222 --> 00:45:05,681
So if I say something about science,

1293
00:45:05,682 --> 00:45:07,422
- I could multiply that by 190.
- That would be a multiple of 190.

1294
00:45:07,652 --> 00:45:09,321
It was very reasonable,

1295
00:45:09,322 --> 00:45:10,391
so I thought it would be a great opportunity.

1296
00:45:10,392 --> 00:45:12,822
I played the games with effort,

1297
00:45:13,192 --> 00:45:16,891
but in the dormitory, I kept talking about science.

1298
00:45:16,892 --> 00:45:19,601
In all my interviews, I started by quoting a scientist.

1299
00:45:19,602 --> 00:45:21,371
"Charles Darwin said this."

1300
00:45:21,372 --> 00:45:23,572
But all those were edited out.

1301
00:45:24,142 --> 00:45:27,242
- They were all...
- So I just became a silent gamer.

1302
00:45:28,312 --> 00:45:29,371
They were all edited out?

1303
00:45:29,372 --> 00:45:31,942
He appeared like a peacekeeper of the Earth there.

1304
00:45:32,182 --> 00:45:33,211
- Let's think of a way...
- You're right, though.

1305
00:45:33,212 --> 00:45:34,412
- we can all survive.
- Yes.

1306
00:45:34,752 --> 00:45:38,782
(He cared about everyone's survival, not just his own.)

1307
00:45:39,722 --> 00:45:42,451
(A new character in a survival show,)

1308
00:45:42,452 --> 00:45:45,122
(who chose coexistence over competition)

1309
00:45:45,492 --> 00:45:47,161
(Is this really for the weak?)

1310
00:45:47,162 --> 00:45:48,791
(How do we define who is weak?)

1311
00:45:48,792 --> 00:45:51,262
(Is it just self-satisfaction?)

1312
00:45:51,562 --> 00:45:53,861
What was nice was that many scientists...

1313
00:45:53,862 --> 00:45:55,732
watched that and reached out to me.

1314
00:45:56,072 --> 00:45:58,971
"You showed people the role of a scientist..."

1315
00:45:58,972 --> 00:46:00,242
"in that small world."

1316
00:46:00,942 --> 00:46:04,511
"Scientists should not profit from what they discovered."

1317
00:46:04,512 --> 00:46:05,981
"They should share it with everyone..."

1318
00:46:05,982 --> 00:46:07,811
"so everyone can survive. That's the most important role."

1319
00:46:07,812 --> 00:46:10,552
- Would you go there again?
- Never.

1320
00:46:11,282 --> 00:46:12,481
- Because...
- Why?

1321
00:46:12,482 --> 00:46:16,252
my personality isn't fit...

1322
00:46:16,392 --> 00:46:18,022
- for survival shows.
- That makes sense.

1323
00:46:18,192 --> 00:46:19,861
I was very stressed.

1324
00:46:19,862 --> 00:46:22,932
I really love cooperating.

1325
00:46:23,262 --> 00:46:25,102
I love solving problems.

1326
00:46:25,232 --> 00:46:28,071
I'm really happy when I find a new problem.

1327
00:46:28,072 --> 00:46:30,572
The show "Great Escape," where Ho Dong was on.

1328
00:46:31,002 --> 00:46:33,271
- On the OTT, - Since it's a team game...

1329
00:46:33,272 --> 00:46:35,641
I'm doing a review on it called "Do You Want to Watch With Me?"

1330
00:46:35,642 --> 00:46:37,511
- Really?
- Yes. I'm doing it live.

1331
00:46:37,512 --> 00:46:39,711
- There...
- "Great Escape" is really nice,

1332
00:46:39,712 --> 00:46:41,651
but don't talk about that in front of Shin Dong.

1333
00:46:41,652 --> 00:46:45,122
He's making a new show called "Great Talchum."

1334
00:46:45,452 --> 00:46:47,351
- He was fired from "Great Escape."
- Right.

1335
00:46:47,352 --> 00:46:48,692
- I'm sorry.
- It's called "Great Talchum."

1336
00:46:49,322 --> 00:46:50,551
I'm enjoying the show.

1337
00:46:50,552 --> 00:46:52,092
Korea's traditional...

1338
00:46:52,192 --> 00:46:54,431
- Shin Dong was good too.
- "Great Talchum."

1339
00:46:54,432 --> 00:46:56,492
- I'm enjoying it a lot.
- You were really good.

1340
00:46:56,562 --> 00:46:58,332
Would you go there again if you were asked to?

1341
00:46:59,102 --> 00:47:00,932
- He...
- I think he would.

1342
00:47:01,502 --> 00:47:05,302
Before it aired, I thought about doing it again.

1343
00:47:05,702 --> 00:47:07,872
- But after it aired, - After watching the show.

1344
00:47:08,212 --> 00:47:09,441
- I thought I shouldn't.
- Why?

1345
00:47:09,442 --> 00:47:12,612
When I watched myself on the show,

1346
00:47:12,982 --> 00:47:15,452
I didn't seem that great.

1347
00:47:15,612 --> 00:47:19,222
It seemed my abilities were limited.

1348
00:47:19,452 --> 00:47:21,791
I thought I shouldn't go to the next one.

1349
00:47:21,792 --> 00:47:24,052
The producer actually called me.

1350
00:47:24,262 --> 00:47:26,092
"Let's do the next one together."

1351
00:47:26,322 --> 00:47:27,461
I guess he liked you.

1352
00:47:27,462 --> 00:47:28,491
So I told him...

1353
00:47:28,492 --> 00:47:29,532
to get lost.

1354
00:47:31,602 --> 00:47:33,761
- You really said that?
- I really did.

1355
00:47:33,762 --> 00:47:35,371
- Really?
- "Am I crazy?"

1356
00:47:35,372 --> 00:47:36,671
- You didn't say, "No thanks."
- You were kind...

1357
00:47:36,672 --> 00:47:37,972
even to difficult customers.

1358
00:47:38,742 --> 00:47:40,541
- But to the producer...
- To the producer.

1359
00:47:40,542 --> 00:47:41,542
(Brother School)

1360
00:47:44,242 --> 00:47:48,012
Now, we'll have a presentation by the transfer students.

1361
00:47:48,212 --> 00:47:50,951
- The first presentation...
- The first presentation

1362
00:47:50,952 --> 00:47:52,451
was prepared by Orbit.

1363
00:47:52,452 --> 00:47:53,951
Come to the center.

1364
00:47:53,952 --> 00:47:55,391
- Orbit.
- Come to the center.

1365
00:47:55,392 --> 00:47:56,851
- Let's go.
- Orbit.

1366
00:47:56,852 --> 00:47:57,862
(Let's go, Orbit.)

1367
00:47:59,722 --> 00:48:00,822
Infinite Track.

1368
00:48:01,162 --> 00:48:02,292
- That also fits.
- Oribit.

1369
00:48:02,892 --> 00:48:05,162
I thought a lot about what topic I should present.

1370
00:48:05,332 --> 00:48:08,072
I decided on a topic that people would be interested in.

1371
00:48:08,332 --> 00:48:09,501
Moving to Mars.

1372
00:48:09,502 --> 00:48:10,672
(Brother Science Lesson One: Moving to Mars)

1373
00:48:10,772 --> 00:48:12,401
We'll go to Mars!

1374
00:48:12,402 --> 00:48:13,502
In 20...

1375
00:48:14,002 --> 00:48:17,111
Would we be able to live on Mars if Earth were destroyed?

1376
00:48:17,112 --> 00:48:18,982
- We would be.
- I think so too.

1377
00:48:19,842 --> 00:48:22,311
- Feel free to ask questions...
- Right.

1378
00:48:22,312 --> 00:48:23,751
- as I present.
- Okay.

1379
00:48:23,752 --> 00:48:25,981
May I use polite words when I'm presenting?

1380
00:48:25,982 --> 00:48:28,151
- As you please, Teacher Or.
- All right.

1381
00:48:28,152 --> 00:48:29,491
- Teacher Or.
- Okay.

1382
00:48:29,492 --> 00:48:32,021
- Please call me Professor Or.
- Professor?

1383
00:48:32,022 --> 00:48:34,292
I was appointed as a special professor...

1384
00:48:34,392 --> 00:48:36,531
- at DGIST.
- Really?

1385
00:48:36,532 --> 00:48:37,631
Yes.

1386
00:48:37,632 --> 00:48:38,931
- Let's go, Professor.
- Okay.

1387
00:48:38,932 --> 00:48:41,332
"If Earth were to be destroyed, could humans live on Mars?"

1388
00:48:41,502 --> 00:48:45,802
We've reached the point where we must think about this realistically.

1389
00:48:46,072 --> 00:48:49,272
That's right. The only planet human beings live on.

1390
00:48:49,912 --> 00:48:51,612
- Earth.
- It's Earth.

1391
00:48:51,812 --> 00:48:54,042
- Earth.
- Here's a rough sketch of it.

1392
00:48:54,212 --> 00:48:57,282
(Earth)

1393
00:48:58,222 --> 00:49:00,421
(The third planet of the solar system,)

1394
00:49:00,422 --> 00:49:02,351
(and the only one known to harbor life)

1395
00:49:02,352 --> 00:49:03,821
Actually,

1396
00:49:03,822 --> 00:49:07,221
there are countless planets like Earth in space.

1397
00:49:07,222 --> 00:49:11,161
- I heard there were thousands.
- For example, around the Sun...

1398
00:49:11,162 --> 00:49:13,502
lie several planets, with Earth among them.

1399
00:49:13,762 --> 00:49:16,031
There are thousands of stars...

1400
00:49:16,032 --> 00:49:18,442
like the Sun in our galaxy alone.

1401
00:49:19,102 --> 00:49:20,302
That's right.

1402
00:49:22,812 --> 00:49:26,111
(Of the roughly 200 billion stars, 7 percent are stars like the Sun.)

1403
00:49:26,112 --> 00:49:28,512
In fact, the universe contains hundreds...

1404
00:49:28,782 --> 00:49:31,181
of billions to even trillions of galaxies like our own.

1405
00:49:31,182 --> 00:49:32,481
- What?
- For real.

1406
00:49:32,482 --> 00:49:33,621
- The galaxy.
- Yes.

1407
00:49:33,622 --> 00:49:34,992
There are infinite numbers of them.

1408
00:49:36,422 --> 00:49:38,291
(The observable universe...)

1409
00:49:38,292 --> 00:49:40,561
(is estimated to contain about 2 trillion galaxies.)

1410
00:49:40,562 --> 00:49:42,731
- When you hold your hand up…
- I'm scared all of a sudden.

1411
00:49:42,732 --> 00:49:45,801
Try holding your hand up and covering the sky.

1412
00:49:45,802 --> 00:49:48,331
Within the tiny area...

1413
00:49:48,332 --> 00:49:50,701
your thumb covers,

1414
00:49:50,702 --> 00:49:53,101
countless galaxies...

1415
00:49:53,102 --> 00:49:56,772
lie beyond imagining.

1416
00:49:57,012 --> 00:49:58,741
In short, there are simply way too many.

1417
00:49:58,742 --> 00:50:01,982
And so, Earth is far from being a unique planet.

1418
00:50:02,082 --> 00:50:05,021
But other planets are incredibly far away.

1419
00:50:05,022 --> 00:50:07,021
Here's an example. How far do you think...

1420
00:50:07,022 --> 00:50:09,752
the closest star to Earth is, not counting the Sun?

1421
00:50:10,152 --> 00:50:11,262
Maybe 500 million light-years away?

1422
00:50:11,562 --> 00:50:12,562
Really?

1423
00:50:12,692 --> 00:50:13,961
- Isn't that going too far?
- We've got...

1424
00:50:13,962 --> 00:50:15,191
light-years for an answer.

1425
00:50:15,192 --> 00:50:16,231
That's amazing.

1426
00:50:16,232 --> 00:50:20,062
(Light-year: the distance light travels in a vacuum in 1 year)

1427
00:50:20,432 --> 00:50:23,372
(1 light-year is approximately 9.46 trillion km.)

1428
00:50:23,502 --> 00:50:26,002
The Sun is about eight light-minutes away from Earth.

1429
00:50:26,172 --> 00:50:27,672
Eight light-minutes, okay?

1430
00:50:27,812 --> 00:50:30,742
That's incredibly far. It takes eight light-minutes.

1431
00:50:31,012 --> 00:50:34,042
The star closest to Earth, aside from the Sun,

1432
00:50:34,182 --> 00:50:35,582
is Proxima Centauri.

1433
00:50:35,682 --> 00:50:39,782
(Sun, Proxima Centauri)

1434
00:50:39,952 --> 00:50:42,422
(Proxima Centauri)

1435
00:50:42,952 --> 00:50:44,621
(The closest star, about 4.24 light-years away from Earth)

1436
00:50:44,622 --> 00:50:46,892
It takes 4.24 light-years to reach that star.

1437
00:50:47,022 --> 00:50:49,161
- How do you get there?
- Can you explain?

1438
00:50:49,162 --> 00:50:50,261
Since it's in light-years.

1439
00:50:50,262 --> 00:50:51,761
If we were to use...

1440
00:50:51,762 --> 00:50:54,902
the current spacecraft technology to convert 4.24 light-years...

1441
00:50:54,972 --> 00:50:58,172
At the speed of those spacecraft, 1 light-year takes 20,000 years.

1442
00:50:58,342 --> 00:50:59,741
- Twenty thousand years?
- How do we get there?

1443
00:50:59,742 --> 00:51:01,141
- In other words, - If it's 20,000 years...

1444
00:51:01,142 --> 00:51:02,641
it takes over 80,000 years.

1445
00:51:02,642 --> 00:51:04,612
How many times must we live and die?

1446
00:51:04,642 --> 00:51:07,951
Human civilization began about 3,000 years ago,

1447
00:51:07,952 --> 00:51:09,411
bringing us to the present age.

1448
00:51:09,412 --> 00:51:11,321
- But...
- There's still a long way to go.

1449
00:51:11,322 --> 00:51:12,621
It takes 80,000 years just to get there.

1450
00:51:12,622 --> 00:51:14,151
- We haven't reached that star yet.
- Exactly.

1451
00:51:14,152 --> 00:51:16,651
There are countless planets like Earth,

1452
00:51:16,652 --> 00:51:18,191
- but they are just too far away.
- We can't reach it.

1453
00:51:18,192 --> 00:51:19,761
Even reaching a neighboring one is impossible.

1454
00:51:19,762 --> 00:51:23,092
That's why scientists' goal is to ensure humanity survives...

1455
00:51:23,292 --> 00:51:25,201
- as long as possible on Earth.
- Right.

1456
00:51:25,202 --> 00:51:27,401
But the climate crisis is approaching.

1457
00:51:27,402 --> 00:51:28,831
- It is.
- The weather has been weird.

1458
00:51:28,832 --> 00:51:29,871
You've heard about it, yes?

1459
00:51:29,872 --> 00:51:31,441
- Greenhouse gases.
- It's scorching hot.

1460
00:51:31,442 --> 00:51:34,571
Greenhouse gases like carbon dioxide and methane...

1461
00:51:34,572 --> 00:51:37,812
act like a blanket, covering the Earth.

1462
00:51:38,012 --> 00:51:40,182
Are greenhouse gases good or bad?

1463
00:51:40,312 --> 00:51:41,451
- Good.
- Correct.

1464
00:51:41,452 --> 00:51:42,651
- It's good.
- Good.

1465
00:51:42,652 --> 00:51:45,022
Greenhouse gases are good. Without them,

1466
00:51:45,382 --> 00:51:47,991
the energy would just bounce back into space,

1467
00:51:47,992 --> 00:51:49,821
making Earth very cold like Mars...

1468
00:51:49,822 --> 00:51:51,461
and really hard for life to survive.

1469
00:51:51,462 --> 00:51:53,791
Our bodies are made of 70 percent water.

1470
00:51:53,792 --> 00:51:56,431
- Right.
- That water needs to stay liquid.

1471
00:51:56,432 --> 00:51:58,231
If it gets too cold, it will freeze.

1472
00:51:58,232 --> 00:52:00,331
The water that carries nutrients through our bodies...

1473
00:52:00,332 --> 00:52:02,872
- wouldn't be able to exist.
- I see.

1474
00:52:03,102 --> 00:52:06,342
Thus, greenhouse gases are essential for life.

1475
00:52:06,542 --> 00:52:08,971
But if these greenhouse gases...

1476
00:52:08,972 --> 00:52:10,971
- keep building up, - If there's too much.

1477
00:52:10,972 --> 00:52:14,012
it's like wearing a puffer jacket in the middle of summer.

1478
00:52:14,112 --> 00:52:16,881
And what would happen? Earth could turn into another Venus.

1479
00:52:16,882 --> 00:52:19,682
- It'd get too hot.
- Venus is closer to the Sun.

1480
00:52:21,022 --> 00:52:22,591
(A planet with thick carbon dioxide and a 470°C surface temperature)

1481
00:52:22,592 --> 00:52:23,751
Because of the blanket,

1482
00:52:23,752 --> 00:52:25,722
the surface temperature reaches up to 470°C.

1483
00:52:25,992 --> 00:52:28,692
That's right. It's as hot as the oven-baked pizza we eat.

1484
00:52:28,732 --> 00:52:30,092
- That sounds delicious.
- Right.

1485
00:52:31,132 --> 00:52:33,061
Either way, we can't go to that planet.

1486
00:52:33,062 --> 00:52:34,231
I thought it'd be warm.

1487
00:52:34,232 --> 00:52:36,772
Keep going, and Earth could become like Venus.

1488
00:52:36,972 --> 00:52:38,741
What now?

1489
00:52:38,742 --> 00:52:40,371
There aren't many planets we can go to.

1490
00:52:40,372 --> 00:52:44,142
In the end, we might have to move to Mars.

1491
00:52:44,942 --> 00:52:47,542
(Mars)

1492
00:52:48,512 --> 00:52:50,481
(A planet with less carbon dioxide than Venus...)

1493
00:52:50,482 --> 00:52:52,852
(and greater habitability in the solar system)

1494
00:52:52,882 --> 00:52:55,621
Of course, the best option is...

1495
00:52:55,622 --> 00:52:57,991
to preserve Earth's environment as it is.

1496
00:52:57,992 --> 00:53:00,122
Ultimately, the problem comes down to energy.

1497
00:53:00,162 --> 00:53:04,431
Producing clean, carbon-free energy will solve the problem.

1498
00:53:04,432 --> 00:53:06,301
It's up to scientists to make it happen.

1499
00:53:06,302 --> 00:53:08,602
Spread the rumor that carbon is good for you,

1500
00:53:08,672 --> 00:53:10,131
and it would quickly decrease.

1501
00:53:10,132 --> 00:53:11,301
- Because we'd consume it?
- Yes.

1502
00:53:11,302 --> 00:53:12,872
Ho Dong, can you not eat carbon?

1503
00:53:13,642 --> 00:53:15,571
- I haven't tried yet.
- Because...

1504
00:53:15,572 --> 00:53:17,311
- Ho Dong likes burnt beef.
- True.

1505
00:53:17,312 --> 00:53:18,882
- Burnt beef.
- He enjoys burnt beef.

1506
00:53:18,982 --> 00:53:20,811
Ho Dong, why are you being such a picky eater?

1507
00:53:20,812 --> 00:53:22,511
- You should eat burnt beef.
- He's on a roll.

1508
00:53:22,512 --> 00:53:24,111
- We do eat carbon.
- True.

1509
00:53:24,112 --> 00:53:27,151
The foods we eat are carbon-based.

1510
00:53:27,152 --> 00:53:28,451
We're carbon-based too.

1511
00:53:28,452 --> 00:53:31,862
But the important thing is that we breathe out carbon dioxide.

1512
00:53:32,022 --> 00:53:34,861
The person who emits the most carbon dioxide is Ho Dong.

1513
00:53:34,862 --> 00:53:37,191
- What? No.
- He takes in a ton of oxygen.

1514
00:53:37,192 --> 00:53:40,032
No, that's not true. But you've made a good point.

1515
00:53:40,102 --> 00:53:42,101
Among us,

1516
00:53:42,102 --> 00:53:45,242
the biggest contributors to reducing greenhouse gases are,

1517
00:53:45,842 --> 00:53:48,511
first, Ho Dong, and second, Jang Hoon.

1518
00:53:48,512 --> 00:53:49,711
- How come?
- Why?

1519
00:53:49,712 --> 00:53:51,481
- Shin Dong also plays a big part.
- Really?

1520
00:53:51,482 --> 00:53:52,981
- Because they're big?
- Since they are big eaters?

1521
00:53:52,982 --> 00:53:56,352
Yes. All living things contain carbon in their bodies.

1522
00:53:56,552 --> 00:53:59,022
The bigger the organism, the more carbon it contains.

1523
00:53:59,622 --> 00:54:01,321
- We're doing an amazing job.
- Totally.

1524
00:54:01,322 --> 00:54:03,351
Those three are basically global warming.

1525
00:54:03,352 --> 00:54:04,391
Because of their big bodies.

1526
00:54:04,392 --> 00:54:05,961
Our whole body is capturing carbon.

1527
00:54:05,962 --> 00:54:07,821
That must be why your body feels so warm.

1528
00:54:07,822 --> 00:54:11,862
Given these issues, we should do everything we can to solve them.

1529
00:54:11,902 --> 00:54:14,162
But ultimately, we must move to Mars.

1530
00:54:14,262 --> 00:54:17,502
Let's assume we don't have the technology to move to Mars.

1531
00:54:17,772 --> 00:54:18,842
What would happen?

1532
00:54:19,072 --> 00:54:21,002
We wouldn't have any solution.

1533
00:54:21,272 --> 00:54:23,941
If we don't start preparing years in advance,

1534
00:54:23,942 --> 00:54:26,441
we won't have the technology to reach Mars even if we want to.

1535
00:54:26,442 --> 00:54:28,281
That's why we're already working on it.

1536
00:54:28,282 --> 00:54:29,312
They're working on it.

1537
00:54:29,512 --> 00:54:32,551
Interestingly, Elon Musk has been officially preparing to...

1538
00:54:32,552 --> 00:54:35,551
move to Mars for the past two years.

1539
00:54:35,552 --> 00:54:37,221
- That's incredible.
- Yes.

1540
00:54:37,222 --> 00:54:40,192
Ideally, we can take anyone who wants to go to Mars,

1541
00:54:40,492 --> 00:54:41,792
we can take to Mars.

1542
00:54:42,262 --> 00:54:46,631
And bring all the equipment necessary...

1543
00:54:46,632 --> 00:54:51,472
to make Mars more self-sustaining, so Mars can grow by itself.

1544
00:54:51,502 --> 00:54:53,642
He's working hard on developing electric vehicles.

1545
00:54:53,702 --> 00:54:56,242
The atmospheric density of Mars is only one percent.

1546
00:54:56,542 --> 00:54:58,881
Internal combustion engine vehicles won't work there.

1547
00:54:58,882 --> 00:55:00,241
- Only electronic vehicles.
- His goal...

1548
00:55:00,242 --> 00:55:03,881
in making electronic vehicles might be to go to Mars.

1549
00:55:03,882 --> 00:55:05,151
- Gosh.
- I know, right?

1550
00:55:05,152 --> 00:55:08,152
Elon Musk is also working on the Starlink system.

1551
00:55:08,392 --> 00:55:10,051
- The satellites.
- Exactly.

1552
00:55:10,052 --> 00:55:12,991
He's trying to cover Earth with thousands of them.

1553
00:55:12,992 --> 00:55:15,692
A satellite system that will cover the entire planet.

1554
00:55:15,962 --> 00:55:18,661
Couldn't the same be possible on Mars? Right?

1555
00:55:18,662 --> 00:55:21,871
If satellites are orbiting Mars...

1556
00:55:21,872 --> 00:55:23,401
and electronic vehicles are running on the surface,

1557
00:55:23,402 --> 00:55:24,972
even autonomous driving could work.

1558
00:55:25,102 --> 00:55:27,372
Some speculate that...

1559
00:55:27,402 --> 00:55:29,471
he's carefully considering many things...

1560
00:55:29,472 --> 00:55:31,441
and planning how to move to Mars.

1561
00:55:31,442 --> 00:55:33,011
If Starlink goes live,

1562
00:55:33,012 --> 00:55:34,881
we'd have Wi-Fi access...

1563
00:55:34,882 --> 00:55:36,451
everywhere on Earth.

1564
00:55:36,452 --> 00:55:37,981
Correct. That was an excellent point.

1565
00:55:37,982 --> 00:55:39,281
But you can't even use Wi-Fi.

1566
00:55:39,282 --> 00:55:40,551
He doesn't know how to connect to it.

1567
00:55:40,552 --> 00:55:41,622
(Dumbfounded)

1568
00:55:41,792 --> 00:55:43,191
- How do I connect to it?
- As far as I know,

1569
00:55:43,192 --> 00:55:44,862
he recently learned how to use Bluetooth.

1570
00:55:46,222 --> 00:55:48,291
He can finally connect his speakers via Bluetooth.

1571
00:55:48,292 --> 00:55:50,991
It's been proven that robots can go to Mars.

1572
00:55:50,992 --> 00:55:53,531
The possibility has been demonstrated.

1573
00:55:53,532 --> 00:55:54,802
Of course, it will take years.

1574
00:55:55,102 --> 00:55:57,071
But can humans go to Mars?

1575
00:55:57,072 --> 00:55:59,801
The only celestial body we've ever...

1576
00:55:59,802 --> 00:56:02,242
set foot on besides Earth is the Moon.

1577
00:56:02,672 --> 00:56:05,212
That's right. Mars is a whole different story.

1578
00:56:05,482 --> 00:56:08,652
The Moon is Earth's only satellite.

1579
00:56:08,782 --> 00:56:11,152
We know its location and simply travel to it.

1580
00:56:11,382 --> 00:56:15,292
But Mars orbits the Sun along with Earth.

1581
00:56:15,822 --> 00:56:19,062
Simply put, meeting a friend at a mall or department store works...

1582
00:56:19,322 --> 00:56:21,561
because you agree on a location beforehand.

1583
00:56:21,562 --> 00:56:24,662
But if you two were wandering around without contacting each other,

1584
00:56:25,002 --> 00:56:26,201
it would be hard to meet up.

1585
00:56:26,202 --> 00:56:27,301
(You're right.)

1586
00:56:27,302 --> 00:56:28,901
Using a direct trajectory,

1587
00:56:28,902 --> 00:56:31,232
a trip to the Moon would take only about three days.

1588
00:56:31,432 --> 00:56:32,941
Right. For Mars,

1589
00:56:32,942 --> 00:56:35,241
even if we pick the perfect timing and the shortest possible distance,

1590
00:56:35,242 --> 00:56:37,612
it would take about six months.

1591
00:56:38,212 --> 00:56:41,281
The launch window is the period when the distance is shortest.

1592
00:56:41,282 --> 00:56:42,582
We say the launch window has opened.

1593
00:56:42,912 --> 00:56:45,181
If we pinpoint the perfect timing, it would take six months.

1594
00:56:45,182 --> 00:56:47,581
If the closest distance takes six months,

1595
00:56:47,582 --> 00:56:48,951
what about at the farthest distance?

1596
00:56:48,952 --> 00:56:51,251
At the farthest distance, it could take up to two years.

1597
00:56:51,252 --> 00:56:53,221
- And so...
- The distance keeps changing.

1598
00:56:53,222 --> 00:56:55,861
Rather than returning immediately after landing on Mars,

1599
00:56:55,862 --> 00:56:58,901
it's more reasonable to wait for the next launch window,

1600
00:56:58,902 --> 00:57:01,431
which could be about a year, before heading back.

1601
00:57:01,432 --> 00:57:03,972
A round trip would therefore take roughly 2 to 2.5 years.

1602
00:57:04,072 --> 00:57:05,242
It's by no means an easy task.

1603
00:57:05,442 --> 00:57:06,772
Coming back is basically impossible.

1604
00:57:06,842 --> 00:57:08,711
- Exactly.
- But if we don't go...

1605
00:57:08,712 --> 00:57:11,011
- The most important question is, - Yes?

1606
00:57:11,012 --> 00:57:13,711
can humans live on Mars?

1607
00:57:13,712 --> 00:57:15,281
Building on what Jang Hoon said,

1608
00:57:15,282 --> 00:57:17,011
let's say we went to Mars with no conditions.

1609
00:57:17,012 --> 00:57:19,321
Is there breathable oxygen so we can survive and walk around?

1610
00:57:19,322 --> 00:57:20,451
- No.
- But why…

1611
00:57:20,452 --> 00:57:21,452
"No?"

1612
00:57:21,453 --> 00:57:23,651
The atmospheric density is only one percent.

1613
00:57:23,652 --> 00:57:24,722
What now?

1614
00:57:24,752 --> 00:57:27,261
And most of it is carbon dioxide. We can't breathe.

1615
00:57:27,262 --> 00:57:29,232
Can't we survive for a short moment?

1616
00:57:29,292 --> 00:57:31,701
Even now, we can hold our breath for a brief time.

1617
00:57:31,702 --> 00:57:32,832
That's about how long it'd be.

1618
00:57:33,232 --> 00:57:34,761
- Is that so?
- Really?

1619
00:57:34,762 --> 00:57:36,001
- True.
- That's not bad.

1620
00:57:36,002 --> 00:57:37,071
It's like being underwater.

1621
00:57:37,072 --> 00:57:39,701
Scientists have conducted several studies.

1622
00:57:39,702 --> 00:57:42,171
"How can we turn carbon dioxide into oxygen?"

1623
00:57:42,172 --> 00:57:44,271
MIT invented a device called MOXIE.

1624
00:57:44,272 --> 00:57:46,981
It has been loaded onto the rover Perseverance,

1625
00:57:46,982 --> 00:57:49,951
which is currently on Mars, for testing.

1626
00:57:49,952 --> 00:57:51,821
Carbon dioxide can be converted into oxygen.

1627
00:57:51,822 --> 00:57:53,751
(Searching for signs of past life...)

1628
00:57:53,752 --> 00:57:55,851
(and testing preparations for human habitation on Mars)

1629
00:57:55,852 --> 00:57:58,492
But the gear needs to run around the clock, and that takes energy.

1630
00:57:58,692 --> 00:58:00,921
- That's right.
- It all comes down to the devices.

1631
00:58:00,922 --> 00:58:02,061
Oxygen is essential.

1632
00:58:02,062 --> 00:58:06,101
Like in the movie "The Martian,"

1633
00:58:06,102 --> 00:58:09,731
we'd need a sealed area with a constant supply of oxygen.

1634
00:58:09,732 --> 00:58:13,641
If we don't develop a sealed space, living on Mars would be impossible.

1635
00:58:13,642 --> 00:58:16,411
Still, making that effort to live there is for the far future.

1636
00:58:16,412 --> 00:58:18,341
- Yes, the far future.
- For our descendants.

1637
00:58:18,342 --> 00:58:20,142
How big is Mars?

1638
00:58:20,442 --> 00:58:22,881
- Mars is big enough.
- Is it similar to Earth?

1639
00:58:22,882 --> 00:58:25,422
Its rotation speed is almost identical.

1640
00:58:25,522 --> 00:58:27,281
(A diameter of about 60,000km, A diameter of about 120,000km)

1641
00:58:27,282 --> 00:58:29,252
(Mars is roughly half as big as Earth.)

1642
00:58:29,422 --> 00:58:30,422
(24 hours and 37 minutes, 24 hours)

1643
00:58:30,423 --> 00:58:33,591
(Mars and Earth have roughly the same rotational speed.)

1644
00:58:33,592 --> 00:58:36,731
Professor, I heard people who had surgery can't get on a spaceship.

1645
00:58:36,732 --> 00:58:38,301
- Right. I heard that it'd explode.
- That's a good question.

1646
00:58:38,302 --> 00:58:39,801
Actually,

1647
00:58:39,802 --> 00:58:41,431
it depends on the surgery.

1648
00:58:41,432 --> 00:58:43,471
To escape Earth's atmosphere and enter space,

1649
00:58:43,472 --> 00:58:46,571
you must overcome incredibly strong gravity.

1650
00:58:46,572 --> 00:58:49,541
When you do that, you might have various difficulties...

1651
00:58:49,542 --> 00:58:50,941
depending on the area of the surgery.

1652
00:58:50,942 --> 00:58:51,942
- For example, - What are some examples?

1653
00:58:51,943 --> 00:58:53,441
intraocular pressure changes when you go to space.

1654
00:58:53,442 --> 00:58:55,851
- Some types of eye surgery...
- He won't be able to go to space.

1655
00:58:55,852 --> 00:58:57,711
- won't be allowed.
- I got intraocular lens implants.

1656
00:58:57,712 --> 00:59:00,151
- A detailed checkup...
- Won't he be able to go to Mars?

1657
00:59:00,152 --> 00:59:01,281
will be needed.

1658
00:59:01,282 --> 00:59:02,921
The blood flow changes.

1659
00:59:02,922 --> 00:59:04,751
Various conditions change.

1660
00:59:04,752 --> 00:59:06,791
Thus, if you had a surgery for a condition that might recur...

1661
00:59:06,792 --> 00:59:08,361
Is it possible to get taller...

1662
00:59:08,362 --> 00:59:09,662
- in space?
- You'll definitely get taller.

1663
00:59:10,292 --> 00:59:12,732
- Will Jang Hoon reach 4m?
- Jang Hoon.

1664
00:59:13,132 --> 00:59:14,361
- Seriously.
- After all,

1665
00:59:14,362 --> 00:59:17,571
gravity decreases when you go to space.

1666
00:59:17,572 --> 00:59:18,872
The distance between the joints increases a bit.

1667
00:59:19,802 --> 00:59:21,471
It's not like we can go to space as we want.

1668
00:59:21,472 --> 00:59:22,771
- We need some time.
- It's possible to go to space.

1669
00:59:22,772 --> 00:59:27,042
SpaceX, a company that studies this matter with seriousness,

1670
00:59:27,382 --> 00:59:30,382
has found rapid success since two years ago.

1671
00:59:30,612 --> 00:59:34,521
It made the biggest spacecraft in human history called Starship.

1672
00:59:34,522 --> 00:59:35,921
- Yes. Starship.
- I've heard of it.

1673
00:59:35,922 --> 00:59:37,651
It consists of Stage One, Super Heavy...

1674
00:59:37,652 --> 00:59:39,521
- and Stage Two, Starship.
- That's right.

1675
00:59:39,522 --> 00:59:42,261
The total length is 120m.

1676
00:59:42,262 --> 00:59:43,291
Simply put,

1677
00:59:43,292 --> 00:59:46,761
It's like the 40-story Tower Palace that'll be launched into space.

1678
00:59:46,762 --> 00:59:50,171
Surprisingly, in just their third year,

1679
00:59:50,172 --> 00:59:52,171
they succeeded in retrieving Stage One.

1680
00:59:52,172 --> 00:59:53,271
- It came back.
- Yes.

1681
00:59:53,272 --> 00:59:55,871
It's impressive technology. It was a massive spacecraft...

1682
00:59:55,872 --> 00:59:57,941
that had never been launched in human history.

1683
00:59:57,942 --> 01:00:00,081
- Seriously.
- In April of 2023,

1684
01:00:00,082 --> 01:00:01,082
it had its first launch.

1685
01:00:01,482 --> 01:00:04,652
(Starship's 1st launch on April 20, 2023)

1686
01:00:05,622 --> 01:00:10,092
(It was the first technical step for the relocation to Mars.)

1687
01:00:10,492 --> 01:00:14,292
(Starship's 5th launch on October 13, 2024)

